          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "REgression",
          "Higher Education",
          "Blended Learning",
          "51 graduate students",
          "2 Consecutive Courses on Statistical Techniques",
          "Questionnaire, Publications on Social Media, Student Characteristics",
          "Problem-Based Learning",
          "[Male, Age, Prior Knowledge, Facebook Stay Time, Facebook Friends, Digital Distraction, Peer Learning Orientation, Peer Learning Engagement]",
          "Prior knowledge comes form a 33 MCQ test done at the start.\n\nDigital distraction was done using Perceived Attention Discontinuity subscale. \n\nPeer learning was extracted using the MSLQ. \n\nThe work involves the of predictive models from 2299 interaction artifacts to predict peer learning. It starts with identifying whether the posts were statistics related or not. \n\nStatistics important posts were analyzed using different NLP representations and subsequently used for prediction using RF, SVM, LSTM or Fully Connected Neural Networks.",
          "Hierarchical Linear Regression",
          "{R-Squared: 0.58 - Model 5, Adjusted R-Squared: 0.49 - Model 5, AIC: 314.76 - Model 5, BIC: 332.67 - Model 4B}",
          "-",
          "The best performing model in terms of hierarchical regression was the one that considered the results of the peer learning predictive model.\n\nObjective peer learning engagement was still a significant predictor of performance in PBL.\n\n",
          "Prior knowledge activation or process orientation feedback can prevent  learners from incorrectly learning. \n\nDigital distractions negstively impact performance. \n\nIt is benefical to introduce timed tasks to help learners focus.\n\nPredicted peer learning was fouond to be more relevant than the perception. \n\nLow number of posts associated withs tatistics was a signifcant predictor of poor performance.\n\nMu.ltimodal Learning Analytics can be sued to identify distractions and predict poor performance.\n\n",
          "Authors use an hierarchical regression model to understand factors behind peer learning. \n\nIn the process, they extract data from multiple sources and compare whether peer learning reported in questionnaire is more predictive than observed behavior.\n\n",
          "Only recruited learners from one specific course. \n\nLimited number of ML algorithms and NLP representations were tested. \n\nCoding as statistics-relevant vs not -relevant, while interesting, could be explored with additional layers.\n\nOnly considers peer learning as part of a facebook group."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 5
    }
  ],
